          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>New York</placeName>
                                        <date>September 22d 1853</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Isaac Leeser Esqr</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Seeing that your<lb/> Bible translation will be
                                        finished this month, I would<lb/> respectfully request you
                                        to forward to me one copy<lb/> bound in morocco gilt Edges
                                        (No 3) at $5 extra.<lb/> with my name attached to it in
                                        full, also one copy<lb/> of your daily Prayer books,
                                        strongly bound with<lb/> “<persName>Lewis A.
                                                  Arnold</persName>” printed on the cover, and<lb/>
                                        one copy of your Day of Atonement Books.<lb/> Please include
                                        Bill for Occident.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I suppose you have heard of the death<lb/> of my
                                        father, who departed this life on the<lb/>
                                        <date>7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of August</date> last at
                                                  <placeName>Jebenhausen</placeName> after only<lb/>
                                        2 days illness, aged not quite 72 years.</p>
                              <p>This sad news came quite sudden upon me<lb/> having received a
                                        letter from my lamented father<lb/> only about 3 weeks ago,
                                        written in the best of<lb/> spirits, and dated <date>August
                                                  5<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>, the very day<lb/>
                                        he was taken sick. Believe me, dear Sir!<lb/> I feel his
                                        loss severely, he was always a good<lb/> father to me, and
                                        although not possessing the<lb/> advantages of a liberal
                                        education, he was always<lb/> alive to every thing advancing
                                        or improving<lb/> our holy religion. Very few men in
                                        his<lb/> neighborhood left a better name for
                                        benevolence.</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>May His soul rest in peace Amen.</p>
                              <p>And now my friend, I have to trouble you to<lb/> answer me a
                                        religious question, which has<lb/> occupied my mind lately.
                                        Since I have been<lb/> in business in this city, I have with
                                        the help<lb/> of God been a strict observer of our holy
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add>.<lb/> This of course is no
                                        credit to any one professing<lb/> Judaism, but you know
                                        human nature well<lb/> enough to appreciate the sacrifice of
                                        worldly<lb/> considerations one has to undergo who has been
                                        <lb/>delinquent in this great duty towards his<lb/> maker. I
                                        come now to the point.<lb/> Notwithstanding observing the
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add> strictly,<lb/> I have at the
                                        same time kept but the 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> day<lb/> of
                                        the holy days <add>Hebrew</add>, and in<lb/> doing so, I
                                        felt myself fully justified, as<lb/> the plain Law of God
                                        only commands us to<lb/> keep each one of these respective
                                        days holy,<lb/> and we have no authority to change it in 2
                                        days,<lb/> as it is written in the same Law of God on
                                        several<lb/> occasions “Ye shall not add unto the word<lb/>
                                        which I command thee, neither shall ye diminish<lb/> ought
                                        from it.” Now my dear friend, how do<lb/> you reconcile
                                        these several passages to this<lb/> rabbinical institution
                                        of ordaining two days<lb/> in place of the highest authority
                                        commanding<lb/> only one? This is my position and
                                        argument.</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>I have never studied traditional law, and as<lb/> it is my wish to
                                        do right in the sight of<lb/> God and men, I take my refuge
                                        to you,<lb/> to inform me on this subject, <sic>wether</sic>
                                        the<lb/> step I have taken is right or wrong.<lb/> Judging
                                        from your past strict Orthodoxy,<lb/> I am almost convinced
                                        beforehand, that you<lb/> will decide against me, however I
                                        have<lb/> full reliance in your Judgment confident<lb/> that
                                        you will give me sufficient proofs to<lb/> uphold your
                                        position, at the same time<lb/> considering the consistency
                                        of my own opinion<lb/> in this matter.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I will say it without meaning<lb/> any flattery to
                                        yourself, that your teaching<lb/> has somewhat made me a
                                        better man,<lb/> and in accordance will with pleasure<lb/>
                                        subject myself to any decision you shall<lb/> be pleased to
                                        pronounce</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">May I beg of you the favor of as early a<lb/>
                                        reply as your occupation will permit.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you many happy returns<lb/> to the
                                        approaching holy days, I remain</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">most respectfully, your friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">
                                        <persName role="author">Lazarus Rinold</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>40 Cedar St</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
